import Foundation

/// Curated per-version highlights. These are the concise "what changed" bullets for the current marketing
/// version; a release cut updates `highlights` and `version` (HARD rule, kept in sync with CHANGELOG.md).
/// The in-app "What's New" screen (Settings > What's New) renders the full bundled CHANGELOG.md and only falls
/// back to these highlights when that resource is absent. Pure logic so it compiles on every target.
enum WhatsNew {
    static let version = "0.3.13"
    static let highlights: [String] = [
        "Pausing a video shortly after starting it no longer crashes the app. The player keeps filling its read-ahead buffer while paused, so a pause right after start parked the app at its peak memory use, and minutes later the screensaver started its own 4K pipeline on top and the system quit the app. After a minute of continuous pause the player now trims its read-ahead and hands the memory back, restores the full buffer the moment you resume, and answers the system's low-memory warning the same way, so an overnight pause with the screensaver on survives. The paused picture never moves and resume continues from the exact frame. From a community contribution by jbecker-it, tested on real hardware. Apple TV, iPhone, and iPad.",
        "Watch progress now saves on every stream, including the files that never report a length. Many direct-play MKVs never announce their duration, and resume, the periodic progress save, marked-as-watched, and Up Next all quietly sat out on them, so exactly those titles always restarted from the beginning. The player now reads the duration itself as soon as playback ticks, so those titles resume like any other. From the same community contribution by jbecker-it. Apple TV, iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "Heavy scrubbing can no longer lose your place or wrongly mark an episode watched. Scrubbing back and forth then exiting could save a stale position from before the scrub; overshooting the end could mark the episode watched, wipe its progress, and move the selector to the next one; and merely passing the ninety percent mark for a moment flipped it to watched. Committed scrubs now hold their target until the player actually lands there, the end of the timeline is held a few seconds short of the credits so only real playback finishes an episode, and watched needs a few settled seconds near the end rather than a fly-by. From the same community contribution by jbecker-it. Apple TV.",
        "Audio no longer crackles or lags after a big seek or an audio or subtitle change on Apple TV. A seek empties the player's forward buffer, and resuming instantly on an empty buffer made the audio engine underrun repeatedly, heard as distortion and a few laggy seconds. The player now takes one short honest buffering pause at exactly those moments and only those moments, so playback resumes once and cleanly while ordinary starts stay as fast as before. From the same community contribution by jbecker-it. Apple TV.",
        "Continue Watching updates the moment you stop watching, and reopening a title right away resumes at the right place. The Home card used to keep its old position until something else refreshed the library, and a quick reopen could start from the beginning and then overwrite the real position. The player now completes its final save and refreshes the library on exit, and when the engine has no usable answer yet the account's own record is consulted, which also knows which episode it belongs to. From the same community contribution by jbecker-it. Apple TV, iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "Add-ons that serve plain HTTP or HLS streams now show their sources. A whole class of add-ons, most live-TV style catalogs among them, embeds its streams inside the catalog entry itself rather than answering a separate stream request, and the app only ever read the separate answer, so those add-ons listed nothing. Both surfaces are now read and merged, so their sources appear and play like any other. Apple TV, iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "An add-on you removed no longer haunts the Home customization list. Removing an add-on kept its catalogs registered under the hood, so its rows still appeared in the customize list and could still render on Home, with no way to clear them. Removed add-ons' catalogs now disappear everywhere immediately, and reinstalling the add-on brings your old arrangement back. Catalog rows sitting behind an add-on a profile has disabled also always load now. Apple TV, iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "The diagnostic log can now be saved or shared directly from Settings, no QR code or second device needed. Save it to Files, AirDrop it, or mail it; it works whenever the log has content, even after you turn Diagnostic logging back off. The QR export stays for Apple TV. iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "Source rows no longer run off the edge on smaller iPhones; the quality and add-on badges scroll gently instead. iPhone.",
        "Where-to-watch service logos are legible everywhere now, sitting on a light plate instead of vanishing into the dark background. Apple TV, iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "Who's watching now appears on iPhone, iPad, and Mac, the way it already does on Apple TV. When you keep more than one profile, the app asks which one to use as it opens, so each person's Continue Watching and library stay their own, and nothing of the main profile shows until a profile is chosen. Switch profile any time from Settings. iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "On the latest Apple systems, the floating player and hero controls pick up Apple's Liquid Glass. The transport buttons over a video, the back and options discs on a title's hero, and the in-player pills take on the new translucent glass look on systems that support it, and keep the current frosted look on earlier ones. It steps aside to the frosted look whenever Reduce Transparency is on, so the controls stay legible. Apple TV, iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "Streaming brands now show their full catalog, and you can choose which services appear. Some brands are listed under several regional or tier ids and only one was being asked for, so a service like Paramount+ showed a handful of stragglers or went missing. Each brand now gathers all of its ids together, so its full catalog fills in, in every region, on the details hub and the Home rails alike. You can also pick exactly which streaming services appear and in what order, from a new list in the streaming section: leave it untouched and everything behaves as before. Apple TV, iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "Continue Watching now advances the right title after you play a download or a pasted link. Progress from those plays could land on the previous title you still had open and nudge its position instead of its own. Closing one of those players now clears the previous title, so each keeps its own place. Apple TV, iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "A title or add-on you removed is even less likely to come back after an update or on a device that was offline for a while. Removals now carry a timestamp, so the most recent action always wins when two devices disagree, and a device returning after a long gap can no longer undo a newer removal. Adding something again clears its removal, as before. Apple TV, iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "Sources are ordered more accurately. A release that only carries foreign subtitles is no longer treated as foreign audio and pushed down, and a title whose name contains a word like Instant no longer shows a false Cached badge. Apple TV, iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "Opening a title with thousands of sources no longer freezes or closes the app. The most popular films can return several thousand sources across your add-ons, debrid account, and the community pool, and past a few thousand an internal cache was clearing and rebuilding on every pass, which piled up on the main thread until the system closed the app (the difference between a title that only lagged and one that crashed). That cache now holds the whole list, so a title with thousands of sources stays up. Further speed-ups for very large lists are on the way. Apple TV, iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "Crashes now write their own report into the exportable diagnostic log, so they can be diagnosed without a Mac or a cable. If the app ever quits unexpectedly, the next launch records what happened, the signal and a stack trace, into the same log you export from Settings and send on, instead of the app just vanishing with nothing to look at. The capture is tiny and always runs; what gets folded into the exportable log follows your Diagnostic logging setting, as the rest of that log does. Apple TV, iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "On Apple TV, the Watch button now holds one position on every title, and you can always move focus back up to the top bar from it. A long synopsis used to push the Watch button further down the screen than a short one did, and once the page had grown that tall, pressing Up from the button could no longer reach the navigation bar. The title's description is now held to a fixed height, so the Watch button lands in the same spot whatever the title, and the path back up to the tabs is kept. Ratings also show on the details page now: an IMDb, Rotten Tomatoes, and Metacritic line appears under the title with no setup, on Apple TV the same as on iPhone, iPad, and Mac. Apple TV, iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "Community (Singularity) sources now reliably show up in the source list. The community pool answered in about half a second, but the screen that asked for it was often replaced before the answer arrived (for example while a title's details were still settling or right after a navigation), and the fetched sources were thrown away with it, so the Singularity group never appeared even though the pool had sources for the title. Fetched community sources are now kept for the whole app session, so the list that is actually on screen gets them, and reopening a title shows its community sources instantly. Requires Singularity sources turned on and a signed-in VortX account, as before. Apple TV, iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "A title you remove from Continue Watching now stays gone after an update, instead of coming back. Dismissing a title from Continue Watching (or removing it from your Library) synced to your account, but a sideloaded update could bring it back: on an update the local engine can come up empty for a moment, and the account then re-added every title it remembered with no record that some had been removed. Removals are now kept in a durable list that syncs with your account, the same way a removed add-on already stays removed, so a dismissed title is left out when the account rebuilds your library. A removal is also pushed right away when you make it (and finishing or rewinding a title is too), and gets a short grace window to finish when the app moves to the background, so an update can no longer interrupt it. Adding the same title again clears its removal. Your other titles and cross-device Continue Watching are untouched. Apple TV, iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "More Dolby Vision MKVs now play as true Dolby Vision instead of dropping to HDR10. Two more sources were still slipping through after the last build's fix: a large 4K hybrid Atmos remux whose rebuilt header outgrew an internal buffer never finished setting up its local stream, and a source whose debrid link answered the very first open with a transient error was given up on instead of retried. The header is now patched correctly at any size, and a transient first-open error retries once, so both play as true Dolby Vision. Fully fail-soft, with the reason recorded in the exportable diagnostics log when a source genuinely cannot. Apple TV.",
        "True Dolby Vision now plays on Apple TV instead of dropping to HDR10. The app streams Dolby Vision to Apple's player as local HLS, but the player was quietly rejecting that stream and failing with an unsupported-URL error, so every Dolby Vision title fell back to HDR10. The reason: the stream offered a single video option tagged as Dolby Vision (HDR), and Apple's player drops an explicitly-HDR option whenever it cannot yet confirm the TV is in an HDR mode at the moment it reads the list, which left nothing to play. This was pinned down with a byte-exact off-device reproduction: the HDR tag alone caused the failure, while a plain, untagged copy of the very same stream was accepted. The stream now also offers a second, plain option pointing at the identical video and segments, so a playable option always survives, while the Dolby Vision picture, its in-frame dynamic metadata, and VortX's own request to switch the TV into Dolby Vision still drive what you see. The player also now waits a little longer, about twenty seconds, for a Dolby Vision remux to show its first frame before falling back, since an accepted stream has to finish opening. It stays fully fail-soft: a source that genuinely cannot play as Dolby Vision still steps aside to the built-in player quickly, with the reason recorded in the exportable diagnostics log. Match Dynamic Range must be on in tvOS Settings, Video and Audio, Match Content. Apple TV.",
        "On Apple TV, the next episode auto-plays again when you resume a show from Continue Watching. An episode would sometimes play all the way through and then drop you back to Home instead of rolling into the next one; now the player fetches the episode list before it starts, so it always knows which episode comes next. A safety net also re-checks at the end of an episode, so a slow-loading show still advances instead of exiting. The last episode still ends the way it should, and movies still stop when they finish. Apple TV.",
        "Subtitles in your language now turn on by themselves from add-ons and the community pool, including on titles you open from the VortX catalogs. When a video has no built-in track in your first or fallback language, the player fetches a matching add-on or community subtitle and switches it on for you instead of leaving subtitles off. Titles opened from our own catalogs were the ones this used to miss, because they are keyed differently under the hood; they are now resolved to the right identity before subtitles are fetched. Picking a subtitle yourself, or Off, is always respected: a list that arrives a moment later never overrides your choice. Apple TV, iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "On Apple TV, Back on the Siri Remote now steps back one screen at a time instead of jumping straight to Home. From a detail page or a Settings sub-screen, Back returns to the previous screen with your place kept; it goes Home only from a tab's first screen, and Back at Home still leaves the app. Apple TV.",
        "Watched titles now show it on their poster: a check badge and a dimmed cover in your Library, matching the episode list. Mark as Watched from a long-press (or finish a title) and the poster says so; Mark as Unwatched clears it. Each profile sees only its own history. Apple TV.",
        "On Apple TV, pressing Back while the Skip Intro, Skip Recap, or Skip Credits pill is showing now just dismisses the pill and keeps playing, instead of exiting the whole player. Press Back again with no pill up to leave as before. Apple TV.",
        "Dolby Vision from an MKV now plays as true Dolby Vision through Apple's player. The app rebuilds the video and streams it to the player as local Dolby Vision HLS, which is the only delivery Apple TV accepts for Dolby Vision. The old delivery handed the player a file shape it will not open for Dolby Vision, so it either could not open the stream or never produced a picture and dropped to HDR10. It is fully fail-soft: if a stream is not producing a Dolby Vision picture quickly it now falls back to the built-in player in about ten seconds instead of making you wait, and every Dolby Vision step is written to the exportable diagnostics log. Match Dynamic Range must be on in tvOS Settings, Video and Audio, Match Content for Dolby Vision to engage. Apple TV.",
        "Playback on Apple TV no longer stutters or slows the app down over a long session. The player was re-deciding which engine to use on every screen refresh, several times a second, and writing a diagnostic line each time; on a long 4K stream that piled up and made the whole app sluggish. The engine is now chosen once when a stream starts, exactly how iPhone, iPad, and Mac already worked.",
        "Audio and subtitle default languages now take a first choice and a fallback, in any language, so when a title has no track in your first language the player uses your second choice instead of nothing. It works for both embedded tracks and add-on subtitles (add-on subtitles are auto-picked by your language now), and a Match audio to subtitle languages option drives both from one list. Turkish, Dutch, Polish, and Swedish were also added to the language lists.",
        "A Dolby Vision MKV that mounted and then failed with 'Cannot Open' now plays as true Dolby Vision, or steps aside instantly with the reason recorded. Apple's player needs the video's setup data in the stream's header, but some rips carry it only inside the video frames, and the rebuilt header came out empty: the movie mounted, Apple's player refused it, and playback dropped to HDR10 only after that failed mount. The remux now checks the header up front, rebuilds it from the first video frame when the file keeps that data in-band (those files play true Dolby Vision now), and when nothing usable exists it falls back to the built-in player immediately, with the exact reason in the exportable diagnostics log. Files that play today are untouched.",
        "The Dolby Vision display-mode request now asks the Apple TV for real Dolby Vision, not HDR10. The request was built with a mode number from years-old tvOS data, and on current tvOS that number means HDR10, so even a healthy true-Dolby-Vision session was literally asking the TV for HDR10. The request is now built through Apple's public API with a genuine Dolby Vision video descriptor, fires before the video mounts (the order Apple requires), and covers native Dolby Vision MP4 and HLS streams too, which never asked the TV to switch at all. Match Dynamic Range must be on in tvOS Settings, Video and Audio, Match Content.",
        "Resuming a Dolby Vision title no longer silently downgrades it to HDR10 with plain surround. The true-Dolby-Vision lane rebuilds the movie on the fly and can only produce it from the beginning for now, but a resume jumped into a position that did not exist yet, so nothing could play and after twenty seconds the player silently fell back to the built-in player (HDR10 plus plain multichannel) on every second and later watch. A resumed Dolby Vision title now starts from the beginning with a short note, your resume point is kept safe, and the log records the reason any time this lane still falls back. Native resume on this lane is a planned follow-up.",
        "The built-in player is honest about Dolby Vision now. It decodes and tone-maps the picture, so it no longer flips the TV into Dolby Vision mode over that output; it requests HDR10 and shows a short 'Dolby Vision title, HDR10 output' note so what the TV badges is what you are getting. True Dolby Vision plays through the dedicated lane in Apple's player, which now asks for the right mode.",
        "The real Dolby Atmos track wins on the true-Dolby-Vision lane. Within your language the lane now prefers the E-AC3 track that actually carries Dolby Atmos, detected from the bitstream itself, ahead of raw channel count, so a bigger non-Atmos track can never shadow the Atmos bed, the only shape the Apple TV lights Atmos from. The produced stream's Atmos signaling is verified and logged once per play.",
        "The silent ways Dolby Vision gets defeated now say so. If Match Dynamic Range is off (it is off by default on every Apple TV), the player shows the exact setting to turn on. If the Player engine override is Always libmpv, a Dolby Vision play says the override is disabling the true-Dolby-Vision lane. The engine route and any fallback reason always land in the exportable diagnostics log now.",
        "A Dolby Vision MKV no longer errors out with 'can't play this file.' A debrid link whose address happened to contain an '.mp4' fragment could be misread and sent to the player that cannot open MKV, which failed. The app now reads the real file name, so those Dolby Vision MKVs take the true-Dolby-Vision path, where the picture is real Dolby Vision and a Dolby Digital Plus / Atmos track passes straight through to your receiver.",
        "Dolby Atmos and surround are no longer lost when a Dolby Vision file lists a stereo or commentary track first. A 4K Dolby Vision rip often carries several audio tracks: the real multichannel bed (often Dolby Digital Plus with Atmos) plus a stereo downmix or a commentary, and some rips list a stereo or commentary track first. The true-Dolby-Vision player lane used to take whichever audio track came first, so on those files it played the stereo or commentary track and dropped Atmos and surround. It now looks at every audio track and keeps the real one: within your original language it prefers the track with the most channels (a commentary or stereo track is one or two channels, the main bed is six or eight), and when two match it prefers the Dolby Digital Plus track that carries Atmos. So the movie's main surround or Atmos bed plays, in the right language, not a stereo dub.",
        "Dolby Vision movies with lossless audio now play as true Dolby Vision. A 4K Dolby Vision file whose only audio is TrueHD or DTS (the shape of most premium 4K files) used to fall back to HDR10, because the player lane that carries true Dolby Vision cannot decode those audio formats. That one audio track is now converted on the fly, while the video passes through untouched, into a multichannel format that lane plays natively, so you get true Dolby Vision video plus full surround sound. Files that already carry a compatible track are unchanged, and anything the converter cannot handle falls back exactly as before, so nothing that plays today can regress. Multichannel sound in the built-in player also now opens at your receiver's real channel count, so 5.1 content is less likely to be quietly downmixed to stereo.",
        "Apple TV can now sign in to your VortX account by QR, not only Stremio. The sign-in screen leads with VortX: it shows a QR code and a short code, you scan it with your phone (or open vortx.tv/approve in a browser) on a device already signed in to VortX, approve, and the TV signs into your VortX account, the one that owns your add-ons, library, and sync. Your account key is handed to that TV with an end-to-end key exchange, so the relay that carries it never sees it. Connecting a Stremio account stays available as a secondary step.",
        "Cached sources on your own AllDebrid or Premiumize account now resolve natively, the same way TorBox already did. A torrent your AllDebrid or Premiumize account has cached gets the instant badge and plays straight through your own account, no waiting on an add-on to resolve it. Real-Debrid removed its cache-check upstream, so Real-Debrid sources still resolve through your add-ons. No change unless you use AllDebrid or Premiumize.",
        "Community sources now play through your own debrid or TorBox, every kind. With community sources turned on and signed in, pooled torrent, usenet, and direct sources all show up and each resolves through your own account (a torrent through your debrid, a usenet source through your TorBox), badged as cached and playing straight through, no add-on in the middle. Only a source's public identity is ever shared; the playable link is re-created on your own device with your own keys.",
        "On Apple TV, pressing Back after auto-play moves you through episodes now returns you to the episode you are actually on, not the one you first pressed play on. If continuous play carried you into a later episode (or the next season), the Details page jumps to that episode and highlights it, so picking up where you are is one press away.",
        "Security hardening for your account and add-ons. Sign-in and recovery now reject a weakened password-hardening setting from a spoofed server before it can touch your key, and the add-on status check no longer pings private or home-network addresses (your own on-device local add-on still works). No change to how anything looks or feels; it just closes a couple of doors.",
        "You can now reorder your add-ons right in the app. Open Add-ons, tap Reorder add-ons, and drag any add-on up or down. That order is the priority order, which add-on's catalogs and sources come first, and it syncs to your other devices and the web dashboard, the same order a drag on the dashboard sets. The list re-sorts the moment you finish. iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "On Mac, opening a title while its sources are still loading no longer crashes the app. Assembling a big source list off the main thread (the freeze fix below) could, on macOS 26, trip a system toolbar bug and force-quit the whole app the moment a movie detail refreshed. The app now guards that system path so the crash can't happen, on every kind of title. Mac only.",
        "A back-to-top button on Home and Discover. Once you scroll past the top, a small button appears in the bottom corner; tap it to jump straight back to the top. Re-tapping the tab still does the same. iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "The Mac app no longer freezes or force-quits while a title's source list loads. On a popular title with a thousand-plus sources, building and ranking that list ran on the main thread several times a second and could lock the app hard enough that you had to force-quit it. The whole list is now assembled and ranked off the main thread and published once, so the window stays responsive and keyboard navigation keeps working while sources stream in. iPhone, iPad, Mac, and Apple TV.",
        "Play from start replays the source you were watching, never a different one. Starting a movie over from the beginning used to re-run source selection and could jump to another source; it now restarts the exact same source from 0:00. Watch Now and picking a source yourself are unchanged.",
        "Continue Watching resumes instantly when you come back soon. A resume re-minted a fresh debrid link every time, a short wait before the player appeared; if you resume within about twenty minutes of last playing, the still-valid link is used immediately so playback starts at once. Older resumes re-mint as before, and a dead link still falls back to a fresh source.",
        "Downloads on iPhone and iPad no longer fail with a false \"not enough storage\" or a cannot-create-file error. A nearly finished download that resumed was checked against its full size instead of the little that remained, and a download that completed while the device was locked could not create its file. Both are fixed, so large downloads finish even overnight with the screen locked.",
        "Dolby Vision now switches your Apple TV into its Dolby Vision mode, not just HDR10. Even when a true Dolby Vision stream was playing, the player lane that carries real DV never asked the TV to light its Dolby Vision mode, so the TV stayed in HDR10. It now requests Dolby Vision for those streams and returns to your default mode afterward (Match Dynamic Range must be on in tvOS Settings, Video and Audio, Match Content). On Mac, Dolby Vision plays as system HDR, which is the ceiling there.",
        "Removing an add-on now also removes its sources immediately. A deleted add-on stopped showing in your add-ons list but its already-loaded sources kept appearing in open source lists until the next load; deleting an add-on now clears its sources from every source list right away too.",
        "Many more streaming services in the hub. The Streaming Services row now surfaces the full set available in your region, from the majors through BritBox, Acorn TV, Shudder, Criterion, MUBI, Curiosity, SkyShowtime, Zee5, SonyLIV, and more, instead of a short top list. Hide any you don't use in the hub's Customize screen. iPhone, iPad, Mac, and Apple TV.",
        "Community (Singularity) sources now include every source type, not just torrents. When you turn on Singularity sources and sign in, the pool now surfaces usenet and direct sources too, and each one resolves through your own debrid or TorBox account, exactly like your add-ons' sources. Shared sources never carry anyone's keys, so a source that needed a private key just won't appear for others; public sources and torrents show for everyone.",
        "Browse by decade. A new Decades section on Home and Discover opens the 2020s back through the 1950s, each with Movies, Shows, the newest of the decade, and what's trending from it. Turn the section, or any single decade, on or off in the hub's Customize screen. iPhone, iPad, Mac, and Apple TV.",
        "Dolby Vision now engages on Apple TV instead of always falling back to HDR10. A Dolby Vision file from debrid takes several seconds to open and start its on-device remux, but Apple TV gave up after only five seconds and dropped to HDR10 before the Dolby Vision conversion had even run (this longer wait was already in place on iPhone, iPad, and Mac but had never been carried over to Apple TV). Apple TV now waits long enough, so Dolby Vision titles, including the dual-layer Profile 7 files most 4K Blu-ray rips use, get their shot at playing as true Dolby Vision. A genuinely dead source still falls back cleanly.",
        "Foreign-dialogue (forced) subtitles turn on by themselves again. When a film is in your audio language but has a few lines in another language, the small track that translates just those lines now appears automatically. It was only ever matched by the word \"forced\" in the track's name, which real forced tracks almost never carry; the app now reads the track's actual forced flag, so it works on debrid and streamed sources too.",
        "The Add-ons screen no longer bogs down the app, especially on Mac. With a full account's worth of add-ons, opening Add-ons could balloon memory and make everything crawl, because each add-on logo was decoded at full resolution; every logo is now loaded at the small size it is actually shown at, so the screen stays light and responsive.",
        "On Apple TV you can now scroll down through your entire installed add-ons list. Focus used to stall at the \"Re-check status\" button and never reach the add-ons below it; the button is repositioned on TV so pressing Down steps into the list and through every add-on. Removing an add-on now always takes effect too, including one that arrived from a sync, instead of the Remove button occasionally doing nothing.",
        "Exporting the diagnostic log now clears it afterward, so your next export only contains what happened since. On Mac the log is copied to Downloads and the live log is reset; on Apple TV and iPhone it resets once the download completes.",
        "A broad reliability and security tune-up under the hood. Dozens of smaller fixes from a full code audit: the source list can no longer hang on an unexpected engine status, a Dolby Vision file that cannot play as true DV falls back to the built-in player faster, deleted add-ons and profiles no longer come back from an out-of-date sync on another device, a rapid double-tap of Next no longer starts two episodes at once, and several player and server resources are cleaned up more reliably.",
        "The next episode is ready before you press Play again. While you watch, the app quietly prefetches and pre-heats the next episode so it starts almost instantly. That only kicked in past the halfway point, measured from the title's length, and many 4K debrid files never report a length, so the prewarm never started for them and the next episode cold-started. It now also prewarms after a couple of minutes of playback when no length is known.",
        "Resuming a title no longer gets stuck loading when its saved link has expired. A resume plays the exact source you last used, but a debrid link expires after a while; when that stale link failed, the player stopped instead of moving on, so it could sit loading for a minute or two. It now still tries your exact source first, but on a hard failure it hops to a fresh source automatically so playback starts.",
        "Dolby Vision now plays from MKVs that carry the Dolby Vision signal inside the video stream, not just in a separate container tag. Some Dolby Vision files describe their DV only in the video bitstream, so the app used to see no Dolby Vision and fall back to HDR10 even though other players show them as DV; it now reads that in-stream signal too (with no rewind, so it still works over debrid).",
        "Community scrub-preview thumbnails stop failing to upload every session. A preview sheet needs at least two frames, but the app tried to send one the instant the first frame was captured, which could never build and was dropped with a misleading error. It now waits until it has at least two frames.",
        "On Apple TV, the audio and subtitle track you pick is check-marked instantly instead of a beat after your tap.",
        "Continue Watching resumes without a long pause. After a recent change that stopped the app re-sending detail data that had not changed, a resume could sit for about ten seconds, or need you to leave and reopen the title, before it played. Your progress and resume point now always count as a change worth acting on, so Continue Watching starts right away again.",
        "The Streaming Services row no longer shows a service twice or drops one. Apple TV+ could appear two times while another service went missing, because a few services are listed under two provider IDs upstream and were counted as separate before the row was trimmed to a fixed number. Those are now merged to one tile first, so each service appears once and the row stays complete.",
        "Dolby Vision keeps playing through a slow debrid stretch instead of stopping early. A Dolby Vision movie that had already started could stop partway when the debrid server delivered a slow chunk, because a brief read stall was mistaken for the end of the file. A stalled read is now retried a few times before giving up, so the movie plays through; a genuinely dead link still falls back to the built-in player cleanly.",
        "Dolby Vision no longer crashes the app a few minutes into a movie. True Dolby Vision could play for a few minutes and then crash the whole app; the on-device buffer feeding Apple's player was reading past the end of its own memory once it started dropping already-watched data to stay small. It now reads from the right place and reclaims that memory, so a Dolby Vision movie plays straight through.",
        "Trailers no longer cut out partway through. A trailer plays its picture and sound as two separate streams fetched in small pieces, and a single hiccup on one piece used to end that stream early, so the video or audio stopped halfway. Each piece is now retried before giving up, so trailers play to the end.",
        "On Apple TV, community (Singularity) sources are back inside the source list. They were pinned above the Watch button before you opened the sources; they now sit inside \"All sources\" with your other add-ons, matching iPhone, iPad, and Mac.",
        "On Apple TV, the sign-in screen now works with the Continuity keyboard. The login fields were requesting saved-password autofill, which stalled the Continuity handshake, so an iPhone or Mac could be detected but never type; that request is gone. QR and link sign-in still work too.",
        "Turning off the Collections hub on Home or Discover no longer blanks it on the other screen. The two shared one set of data, so switching it off on one screen also cleared it on the other until a refresh; each screen is now left untouched.",
        "Downloads recover from a transient save error on iPhone and iPad. When the background download service briefly could not create a download's file (even with plenty of free space), the download used to fail outright; it is now retried once automatically before showing an error.",
        "Dolby Vision for MKV actually plays now. Turn on \"Dolby Vision for MKV (Beta)\" in Settings and a Dolby Vision .mkv from debrid plays as true Dolby Vision through Apple's player instead of quietly falling back to HDR10. The source opens reliably on slow debrid links, the on-device remux now produces a stream Apple's player accepts, and the player waits long enough for a Dolby Vision remux to show its first frame instead of dropping to the built-in player too early. The setting is now per-device so it actually sticks. Files that genuinely can't be remuxed still fall back to HDR10 cleanly.",
        "Timeline scrub-preview thumbnails now upload reliably for long movies and full series, not just short clips. A long watch built a preview sheet too large to send, so it was silently dropped and never shared; the sheet is now always sized to fit, decimating across the whole title and shrinking further only if needed, so scrub previews come together for everyone on long titles too.",
        "Watch Now now plays the exact source shown on the button. When the button says 4K Dolby Vision, it no longer quietly starts a lower-quality source that happened to resolve a moment sooner: it plays the source you were shown, so Dolby Vision titles play as Dolby Vision. Picking a specific source yourself still plays exactly that one, and Watch Now still moves on if the top source is genuinely unavailable.",
        "On Mac, Export diagnostic log now saves the log to your Downloads folder and reveals it in Finder, instead of asking you to connect to Wi-Fi.",
        "The Streaming Services tiles now look like the ones on the Apple TV app. Each tile is filled edge to edge with the service's own brand color, with its logo centered on top: Netflix on a white tile, Disney+ and Prime Video and Paramount+ on blue, Apple TV+ on black, Hulu on black with its green logo, Crunchyroll on orange, and more. No more logo floating on a small white card.",
        "Playback starts right away again. Tapping a source, or Watch Now, now begins in a second or two instead of loading for up to half a minute and flashing \"source failed\" first. When a source cannot open on the native player it falls back to the built-in player on the same source instantly, so you get the source you picked rather than a lower-quality one, and HLS and Dolby Vision still play on the native player.",
        "Posters are bigger by default. Catalog and rail cards now open at a larger, more cinematic size out of the box on iPhone, iPad, and Mac, and you can still tune the size in Settings, Appearance, Poster Style.",
        "Continue Watching now clears titles you have finished. A movie you watched to the end, marked as watched, or finished on another device no longer lingers in the row, and a series you are partway through still shows so you can pick up the next episode.",
        "The Streaming Services logos are now clearly legible. Each brand logo fills most of its tile, so marks like Apple TV+ and Paramount+ read clearly, and a service with no available logo shows its full name instead of a single letter.",
        "Account sync no longer silently drops a change when two devices save at the same moment, and your add-on order now stays consistent across your devices and the web dashboard.",
        "A cleaner, more cinematic look: full-bleed artwork, a bold new Play button, and a more spacious, premium layout across the app. On Mac the design now uses the full width of the window, with a larger hero and a roomier reading column instead of a stretched phone layout.",
        "Dolby Vision now plays from Dolby Vision MKV files, with true DV passthrough (turn it on in Settings). Dual-layer Profile 7 files, the kind most 4K Blu-ray rips use, now play as true Dolby Vision too instead of tone-mapping to HDR10. When a file genuinely can't do true DV (no Dolby Vision data or unsupported audio), playback still falls back to HDR10 automatically instead of erroring, and the engine never switches mid-movie.",
        "Community subtitles now appear in the player's subtitle panel again when you are signed in to VortX, are selectable, and load and stay in sync, plus an \"also available in\" language row on every title.",
        "Add-on subtitles reliably appear in the player's subtitle panel again, including on streams that never report a duration.",
        "Continue Watching resumes faster and more reliably, straight from your debrid account.",
        "Install add-ons by scanning a QR code with your phone, no typing on the TV.",
        "Titles, posters, and logos now show in your language across every catalog, with a region picker and per-category Discover controls in Settings.",
        "Resume timestamps, poster style options, a working subtitle-sync control, and cached-source lightning.",
        "Detail-page polish: a tap-to-expand Cast & Crew section, a \"More Like This\" row that follows your poster style, a poster-labels toggle right in Settings, and an option to combine Discover and Search into one tab.",
        "The player scrubber now shows how much has buffered ahead, with a light grey track behind the playhead, just like YouTube.",
        "Trending, genre and streaming-service tiles now open straight to full details, ratings, artwork and playable sources on iPhone, iPad and Mac, and catalogs keep showing posters and art even when the source is busy.",
        "More reliable downloads, and on Apple TV the \"also available in\" row now shows full language names instead of codes.",
        "The full-trailer button now works on every Apple TV, including the no-server Lite build, and a new Trailer language option in Settings picks trailers in your preferred language.",
        "Offline HLS downloads on iPhone and iPad: adaptive streams now download properly for watching offline, and switching between catalog categories no longer sticks on a loading spinner.",
        "The muted trailer that plays behind the hero on Home and detail pages is now the real full trailer, played quietly and looping, the same source as the Trailer button. When a title has no trailer, the still artwork stays as before.",
        "The Streaming Services tiles now show each service's real brand logo, built into the app and sized to fill the tile, so Netflix, Prime Video, Disney+, Max, Apple TV+ and more appear instantly and cleanly. A service with no available logo shows its full name, like Hulu, Peacock or BBC iPlayer, never a single letter.",
        "Scrub-preview thumbnails now build and share from every title you watch, including everything opened from the Streaming Services, Trending and genre collections. Previously those plays were skipped, so timeline previews stayed empty; now every watch makes scrubbing better for everyone.",
        "Trailers now play straight from your own device at up to 1080p, resolved on the spot instead of routed through a server, so they start faster and look sharper. The ambient trailer behind the hero uses the same path, and many trailers that used to say the source did not load now play reliably.",
        "Cached sources start faster: when a source that looks cached is not actually ready on your account, the player now moves on in a couple of seconds instead of waiting out a long timeout, so you reach a source that plays much sooner.",
        "Pause and cancel now keep working on a download even after you fully quit and reopen the app: an in-progress download that kept running in the background is picked back up on launch, so its Pause and Cancel controls act on the real transfer again instead of doing nothing.",
        "Watch Now reaches a playable cached source much faster: it now checks the top few cached sources at once and plays the first one that is really ready on your account, instead of trying them one at a time. Picking a specific source yourself still plays exactly that one.",
        "Singularity sources now actually show. When you sign in to VortX and turn on Singularity sources in Settings, community-corroborated sources appear in the source list alongside your own, on iPhone, iPad, Mac and Apple TV. Previously the toggle checked the wrong sign-in and the extra sources never loaded.",
        "Removing an add-on now sticks everywhere. When you delete an add-on on the web dashboard or in the app, it stays gone across your devices and no longer reappears after a Stremio import or a background refresh. Installing the same add-on again later still works.",
        "Posters load reliably and the app is snappier on open. Catalog and hero artwork now uses a much larger image cache and loads a few at a time in the background, so posters no longer come back blank and the app stays smooth while you scroll. Turning the Collections hub on Home or Discover on or off no longer strips artwork from the rows below it.",
        "The source you pick is the source that plays, including when you resume from Continue Watching. When you choose a specific 4K, HDR or 1080p source, the player now waits for that exact source instead of quietly dropping to a lower-quality one, and a large 4K file that is still filling gets extra time to start rather than being given up on. Watch Now still moves on automatically when a source is genuinely dead, but it no longer falls all the way to a 480p link when a cached higher-quality one exists, and the \"tried several sources\" message no longer flashes while a source is still starting.",
        "Scrub-preview thumbnails now build from every device, including 4K, HDR and Dolby Vision playback on Mac and iPhone. A capture-timing issue meant some plays generated previews locally but never shared them; timeline previews now come together faster for everyone across all your devices.",
        "On Apple TV the audio and subtitle track menus now show full language names, like English, French and Italian, instead of short codes such as en, fre or ita, matching iPhone, iPad and Mac.",
        "Continue Watching resumes the exact source you last played. Tapping a title in the row now reopens the same debrid file with a fresh link, so it starts on the source you chose instead of dropping into \"tried several sources\" and picking a different, often lower-quality one. If that source is genuinely gone, it still falls back to finding another.",
